---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
const data = {
  metaTitle: "AI Document Processing & Data Extraction | All Webbed Labs",
  metaDescription: "How we built an AI-powered invoice processing pipeline for a Melbourne national logistics company — reducing manual data entry by 89%, cutting errors from 3.2% to 0.4% and tripling processing capacity.",

  industry: "AI & Automation",
  tags: ["Document AI", "OCR", "GPT-4", "Python", "SAP Integration"],

  title: "Document Processing & Data Extraction",
  summary: "A national Melbourne logistics company was paying six accounts payable staff to manually key data from 500 supplier invoices per day — invoices arriving in 180 different formats via PDF, scanned image and fax-to-email. A 3.2% data entry error rate was costing them in payment disputes and reconciliation. We built an AWS Textract and GPT-4 powered processing pipeline with confidence scoring, a human-review queue and direct SAP integration.",

  heroImageDescription: "Document processing pipeline dashboard showing invoice queue with confidence scores, extracted field previews, exception queue for human review, SAP posting status and daily throughput metrics across invoice sources",

  clientOverview: "Placeholder Logistics is a national freight and supply chain company headquartered in Melbourne, managing inbound freight for over 300 Australian and international suppliers. Their accounts payable function processes supplier invoices from 180 different supplier relationships — each with their own invoice format, field layout and data quality standards. At 500 invoices per day across a five-day week, the AP team was processing approximately 10,000 invoices per month. Six full-time AP staff were spending approximately 70% of their working time on manual data entry into SAP.",
  clientSize: "National operations, 6-person AP team",
  clientLocation: "Melbourne, VIC (national operations)",

  pullQuote: "The 3.2% error rate sounds small until you're having a payment dispute with a supplier over $60,000 because someone typed the wrong ABN. We had reconciliation work that was coming back to us weeks later. Fixing data quality at the source was the whole game.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Karen B.",
  pullQuoteRole: "Head of Finance Operations, Placeholder Logistics",

  challenge: [
    "The invoice input diversity was the core technical challenge. Supplier invoices arrived via three channels: email PDF attachments (approximately 60% of volume), scanned image attachments including TIFF and JPEG from older suppliers still using fax-to-email services (approximately 30%), and a small volume of structured EDI or CSV formats. Within the PDF and image categories, there was no standardisation — 180 different suppliers meant up to 180 different field layouts, font sizes, table structures and quality levels. A rule-based extraction approach (template matching or positional extraction) would have required maintaining 180 templates and would have broken every time a supplier changed their invoice format.",
    "OCR quality varied enormously across invoice types. High-quality PDF invoices from large suppliers OCR'd cleanly and consistently. Fax-to-email invoices from smaller regional suppliers could arrive at 100 DPI with handwritten corrections, faded print and coffee stains. The extraction system needed to handle this quality range gracefully, not fail silently — a partially extracted invoice posted to SAP with missing or incorrect fields was worse than an unprocessed invoice that stayed in the queue.",
    "The 3.2% manual data entry error rate compounded the extraction challenge with a quality baseline problem. The existing manual process had known accuracy issues that SAP's three-way matching process (purchase order, goods receipt, invoice) was catching in approximately 160 invoices per month — each generating a payment hold, a supplier query, an AP staff resolution cycle, and a corrected posting. The total cost of this error-correction cycle was estimated internally at 2.5x the original processing cost for the affected invoices.",
    "SAP integration was non-trivial. The client's SAP instance was a heavily customised ERP deployment used for both domestic and international supplier management, with different posting templates for different supplier categories, different tax code logic for Australian GST versus international invoices, and a supplier master data structure that our extraction output needed to map to precisely. Direct integration via SAP's API required understanding not just the API but the business rules embedded in the ERP configuration.",
    "The Australian Privacy Act was relevant to this project because supplier invoices can contain personal information — particularly invoices from sole traders and small businesses where the invoice contains the owner's name, ABN, bank account details and address. These details are personal information under the Privacy Act. Processing, storing and transmitting this data required appropriate controls, and retention policies needed to reflect the Privacy Act's requirement that personal information not be retained longer than necessary for the purpose.",
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The client had evaluated two commercial invoice automation vendors before engaging us. One was a large enterprise AP automation platform with a per-invoice pricing model that, at the client's volumes, would have cost more than the current staff time it was replacing. The other was a smaller point solution with strong OCR capabilities but no AI extraction layer — it required template configuration per supplier, which the client had neither the time nor internal expertise to maintain.",
    "We were referred by the client's IT consulting firm, who had worked with us on a previous data pipeline project. The referral context was specific: 'they actually understand how to work with messy real-world documents, not just clean test data'. This matched the client's core concern — vendors who had demoed well on sample invoices from major suppliers but hadn't been honest about performance on low-quality source documents.",
    "We proposed a confidence-scoring and human-review queue architecture from the first meeting, which resonated immediately with the AP team lead. Her concern was not just automation accuracy — it was what happened when the system got things wrong. A system with a visible, manageable exception queue felt trustworthy in a way that a black-box system with high claimed accuracy did not. The human-in-the-loop design was a deliberate feature, not a concession.",
  ],

  approach: [
    "We began with a two-week document audit, processing 500 real invoices from the client's archive across all 180 suppliers. Every invoice was manually labelled with the correct field values: supplier name, ABN, invoice date, invoice number, line items, amounts, GST amounts and bank details. This labelled dataset served two purposes: it was our ground truth for accuracy measurement throughout development, and it revealed the actual distribution of document quality — which was considerably worse at the tail than the client's samples had suggested.",
    "The audit identified that 23% of invoices had at least one quality characteristic that would challenge standard OCR: fax degradation, scanned at below 150 DPI, handwritten corrections over printed fields, or non-standard character encoding in PDF text layers. This 23% was the primary driver of our two-stage architecture: AWS Textract for initial OCR and structural extraction, followed by a GPT-4 post-processing step to handle ambiguous and low-confidence extractions.",
    "We chose a confidence-scoring architecture over a pure accuracy target for a specific reason: invoice processing accuracy is not uniform across fields. Getting the invoice total wrong is far more consequential than getting the invoice date wrong by a day. The confidence scoring system assigns field-level confidence scores (not just document-level) and routes documents to the human review queue based on the confidence of the specific high-stakes fields — invoice number, total amount, ABN, and bank details — rather than average document confidence.",
    "Airflow was chosen for pipeline orchestration because the invoice processing workload has complex retry semantics. A failed Textract job should retry before escalating. A GPT-4 field extraction failure on a specific field should not fail the entire document. A SAP posting failure due to a temporary API timeout is different from a posting failure due to a data validation error. Airflow's DAG structure and task-level retry configuration handled these distinctions cleanly.",
  ],

  solution: [
    "The processing pipeline runs in four stages. Stage one is ingestion: invoices are collected from the email inbox via IMAP, a monitored network folder for EDI files, and a legacy fax-to-email adapter, then normalised to a common document format and queued in Airflow for processing.",
    "Stage two is OCR and structure extraction via AWS Textract. Textract's Analyse Document API (with form and table analysis enabled) extracts text, form key-value pairs and table structures. For high-quality PDFs from large suppliers, Textract alone achieves extraction accuracy above 97% on structured fields. For lower-quality documents, Textract provides the raw text and layout information that feeds into stage three.",
    "Stage three is AI field extraction and validation via GPT-4. The Textract output — structured as a JSON representation of the document's text blocks, key-value pairs and tables — is passed to GPT-4 with a structured prompt requesting extraction of specific fields in a defined JSON schema. GPT-4's strength in this stage is not OCR (Textract handles that) but semantic understanding: correctly identifying that 'Tax Invoice Date' and 'Invoice Dated' and a date that appears after the supplier name are all referring to the same field, even when the layout varies between supplier formats. The model also handles common corruption patterns — partially obscured characters, OCR misreads that can be inferred from context — that rule-based systems cannot.",
    "Stage four is validation, confidence scoring and routing. Extracted fields are validated against business rules: ABNs are checked against the ATO's ABN lookup API, bank BSBs are validated against the BSB directory, and amounts are cross-checked internally (line items should sum to subtotal; subtotal plus GST should equal total). Each field receives a confidence score combining the Textract confidence, the GPT-4 extraction reasoning quality (assessed via a structured self-assessment step in the prompt), and the business rule validation result. Documents where any high-stakes field falls below the confidence threshold are routed to a human review queue; documents above the threshold are auto-approved and queued for SAP posting.",
    "The SAP integration uses the client's configured RFC/BAPI interface to post invoices to the correct AP module. The posting logic includes supplier category routing (domestic vs international, standard terms vs consignment), GST tax code selection based on ABN validation and invoice classification, and duplicate detection by invoice number and supplier ABN combination before posting to prevent double-payment.",
  ],

  implementation: [
    "The project ran over 16 weeks from discovery to production go-live. The document labelling and model evaluation phase ran through weeks one to four. Pipeline development occupied weeks five through ten, with SAP integration development running in parallel. A four-week parallel-run period followed in which the automated pipeline processed all real invoices, but postings were held and reviewed by the AP team before submission to SAP.",
    "The parallel-run period was critical to building AP team confidence and calibrating the confidence thresholds. During the first week, the system routed 31% of invoices to human review — too high for the operational goal of reducing manual workload. Analysing the review queue revealed that the majority of escalations were from a small number of supplier formats that the model consistently struggled with. We added targeted prompt examples (few-shot examples) for these supplier types, reducing the review queue to 9% by the end of the parallel run.",
    "Data privacy controls were implemented at the pipeline level. Supplier invoice data containing personal information (sole trader details, individual names, bank accounts) is encrypted in transit and at rest, processed only within the AWS ap-southeast-2 region, retained for 7 years (consistent with ATO tax record retention requirements, which governed the retention obligation here) and then deleted. Processing logs retain extracted field identifiers but not raw OCR text containing personal information beyond the processing window.",
    "The human review queue interface was built to minimise the cognitive load on AP reviewers. Each queued document displays: the original invoice image, the extracted fields with colour-coded confidence indicators (green/amber/red), the specific fields flagged as low-confidence, and a one-click approval or field-correction workflow. Reviewers do not need to key data manually — they either confirm the extraction or correct specific fields, and the corrected extraction is fed back as a training signal for future improvement.",
    "Post-production, we established a monthly accuracy review process: a random sample of 100 auto-approved invoices is manually reviewed by a senior AP staff member to validate that the auto-approval threshold remains appropriate. If the sampled error rate exceeds 0.5%, the confidence threshold is tightened and the model prompt is reviewed. This process has run for six months post-launch without requiring a threshold adjustment.",
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "Document diversity is always worse than clients initially report. The '500 different formats' challenge is almost always underestimated in scoping conversations because clients typically sample their best invoices. The 23% of documents with quality issues in this project is typical — real-world document AI projects need to be architected for the tail, not the median. This means every project now includes a mandatory document audit phase using real production samples before we scope the technical solution.",
    "GPT-4 field extraction is powerful but requires careful prompt engineering for structured output reliability. In early iterations, the model would occasionally return fields in inconsistent JSON structures or include explanatory text mixed with the structured output. Enforcing strict JSON schema output via the OpenAI function calling interface (rather than free-form JSON in the prompt response) eliminated this class of issue almost entirely.",
    "Confidence scoring at the field level, not the document level, was the right design. A document with 95% average field confidence can still have a zero-confidence invoice total if the total field was obscured. Document-level confidence averaging would have auto-approved these documents; field-level scoring correctly escalated them. The extra implementation complexity of field-level scoring was justified.",
    "The SAP integration was the longest part of the project, not the AI pipeline. We had underestimated the complexity of the client's SAP configuration in the initial scoping. SAP ERP customisations are often extensively documented internally but that documentation is inconsistent and sometimes wrong. Future projects involving ERP integration should budget more discovery time and earlier access to the ERP configuration documentation.",
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Following the successful invoice processing deployment, the client commissioned a second phase to extend the same pipeline architecture to processing freight proof-of-delivery documents (PODs) — a high-volume document type with similar format diversity challenges. The POD processing system extracts delivery confirmation data, GPS timestamps, recipient signatures and exception notes to update the freight management system automatically.",
    "The AP team members redeployed from manual data entry into vendor relationship management and exception handling reported higher job satisfaction in a six-month check-in. The AP team lead noted that the quality of supplier relationships had improved because her team was spending time on escalations and exceptions that genuinely needed human attention, rather than being consumed by data entry.",
    "The client's parent company, having seen the results, engaged us to scope a similar document processing system for their finance subsidiary, which processes a different document type — commercial insurance certificate of currency documents — at comparable volumes.",
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "The automated pipeline reduced manual data entry time by 89% — from approximately 70% of six AP staff members' time to approximately 8%. Daily processing capacity tripled from 500 invoices (manual ceiling) to 1,800 invoices, removing the backlog that had been building when invoice volumes peaked. Data entry error rate fell from 3.2% to 0.4%, directly reducing payment disputes, supplier relationship friction and the costly error-correction cycle. Processing cost per invoice fell 81%. Six AP staff members were redeployed to vendor management and exception handling roles — work that was previously squeezed out by manual entry volume.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "89%", label: "Reduction in manual data entry time", context: "From ~70% of 6 staff members' time to ~8%" },
    { value: "1,800/day", label: "Invoice processing capacity", context: "Up from 500/day manual ceiling — 3.6x capacity increase" },
    { value: "0.4%", label: "Data entry error rate", context: "Down from 3.2% — directly reducing payment disputes and reconciliation" },
    { value: "81%", label: "Reduction in processing cost per invoice", context: "Automated handling vs fully manual AP workflow" },
    { value: "67%", label: "Reduction in payment disputes", context: "Driven by improved extraction accuracy and SAP duplicate detection" },
    { value: "6 staff", label: "AP staff redeployed to higher-value work", context: "To vendor relationship management and exception handling" },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "AWS Textract", reason: "OCR and structural extraction (form key-value pairs, tables); handles high-quality PDFs with near-perfect accuracy, provides layout information for low-quality documents" },
    { name: "GPT-4 (field extraction)", reason: "Semantic field extraction and disambiguation on ambiguous documents; handles format variation and OCR imperfections that rule-based extraction cannot" },
    { name: "Python", reason: "Core pipeline language; Textract SDK, OpenAI SDK, SAP BAPI integration, confidence scoring logic and Airflow DAG definitions" },
    { name: "Apache Airflow", reason: "Pipeline orchestration with task-level retry semantics; distinguishes transient failures (retry) from data validation failures (human escalation)" },
    { name: "FastAPI", reason: "Internal API for the human review queue interface; handles queue management, correction submission and approval workflows" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Invoice processing state, extraction results, confidence scores, review outcomes and accuracy monitoring data" },
    { name: "SAP (BAPI/RFC integration)", reason: "Direct AP module posting via configured RFC interface; includes supplier routing, GST tax code logic and duplicate detection" },
    { name: "AWS (ap-southeast-2)", reason: "All processing infrastructure in Sydney region; Privacy Act compliance for personal information in supplier invoices" },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "Customer Service AI Chatbot",
      href: "/case-studies/customer-service-ai-chatbot",
      industry: "AI & Automation",
      summary: "GPT-4 powered chatbot for a Queensland regional telco resolving 71% of enquiries without human escalation, cutting wait times from 18 minutes to under 2 minutes.",
    },
    {
      title: "Sales Forecasting & Demand Planning Tool",
      href: "/case-studies/sales-forecasting-demand-planning",
      industry: "AI & Automation",
      summary: "ML-powered demand forecasting for a national FMCG distributor, reducing overstock write-downs by 23% and improving forecast accuracy from 31% to 14% MAPE.",
    },
    {
      title: "Expense Management & Approval Workflow",
      href: "/case-studies/expense-management-approval-workflow",
      industry: "AI & Automation",
      summary: "Automated expense processing and policy compliance checking for a national professional services firm, reducing processing time and out-of-policy claim rates.",
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: "AI Document Processing", href: "/services/ai-document-processing" },
    { title: "AI Integration & Automation", href: "/services/ai-integration-automation" },
    { title: "Data Pipeline Development", href: "/services/data-pipeline-development" },
    { title: "ERP Integration", href: "/services/erp-integration" },
  ],
};
